Asymmetric Encryption 

⸻

1. Core Concept
	•	Uses two keys (key pair):
	•	Public Key → shared openly
	•	Private Key → kept secret

Public Key → Encrypt  
Private Key → Decrypt


⸻

2. Why Asymmetric Encryption is Needed

Problem with Symmetric Encryption
	•	Requires secure channel to share key
	•	Not scalable (many users → many keys)

⸻

Solution (Asymmetric)
	•	No need for secure channel
	•	Only need reliable channel (integrity)
	•	Public key can be shared safely

⸻

3. How Key Pair Works

Case 1 — Confidentiality

Alice → encrypt with Bob’s PUBLIC key  
Bob → decrypt with his PRIVATE key

✔ Only Bob can read the message

⸻

Case 2 — Authenticity (Digital Signature)

Bob → encrypt/sign with PRIVATE key  
Anyone → verify using Bob’s PUBLIC key

✔ Confirms message came from Bob

⸻

4. Security Properties

1. Confidentiality
	•	Only intended recipient can decrypt

⸻

2. Integrity
	•	Any change → decryption fails / invalid

⸻

3. Authenticity
	•	Confirms sender identity

⸻

4. Non-repudiation
	•	Sender cannot deny sending message

⸻

5. RSA (Core Algorithm)
	•	Based on:
	•	Two large prime numbers (p, q)
	•	Hard problem: factorization

⸻

Keys

Public Key  = (N, e)  
Private Key = (N, d)


⸻

Process
	•	Encryption:

y = x^e mod N

	•	Decryption:

x = y^d mod N


⸻

Key Idea
	•	Easy: multiply primes
	•	Hard: reverse (factor N)

⸻

6. Real Key Generation (OpenSSL)

⸻

Generate Private Key

openssl genrsa -out private-key.pem 2048

	•	Creates RSA private key (2048-bit)

⸻

Extract Public Key

openssl rsa -in private-key.pem -pubout -out public-key.pem


⸻

View Key Details

openssl rsa -in private-key.pem -text -noout

	•	Shows:
	•	modulus (N)
	•	publicExponent (e)
	•	privateExponent (d)
	•	primes (p, q)

⸻

7. Encryption & Decryption (RSA)

⸻

Encrypt (using public key)

openssl pkeyutl -encrypt \
-in plaintext.txt \
-out ciphertext \
-inkey public-key.pem -pubin


⸻

Decrypt (using private key)

openssl pkeyutl -decrypt \
-in ciphertext \
-inkey private-key.pem \
-out decrypted.txt


⸻

8. Important Notes
	•	Asymmetric encryption is slow
	•	Used mainly for:
	•	Key exchange
	•	Authentication
	•	Digital signatures

⸻

9. Hybrid Encryption (Real-world)

Asymmetric → exchange key  
Symmetric → encrypt data

✔ Used in:
	•	HTTPS
	•	SSH
	•	VPNs

⸻

10. Key Takeaways
	•	Two-key system solves key exchange problem
	•	Public key → share
	•	Private key → protect
	•	Provides:
	•	Confidentiality
	•	Integrity
	•	Authenticity
	•	Non-repudiation

⸻

11. One-line Summary

Asymmetric encryption uses a public-private key pair to securely exchange data without needing a secure channel, enabling confidentiality and authentication.